{"title_page": "St George's School, Edinburgh", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = St George's School for Girls\n | image                   = St_George's_School_for_Girls,_Edinburgh_Logo.png\n | image_size              = 100px\n | caption                 = St George's School for Girls, Edinburgh Logo\n | motto                   = ''Trouthe and honour, fredom and curteisye''\n | established             = 1888\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Independent school (UK)|Independent]] day and [[boarding school|boarding]]\n | religious_affiliation   = Non-denom\n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headteacher\n | head                    = Alex Hems MA Oxon\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = \n | chair                   = \n | founder                 = Dame Sarah Mair\n | specialist              = \n | address                 = Garscube Terrace\n | city                    = [[Edinburgh]]\n | county                  = City of Edinburgh\n | country                 = Scotland\n | postcode                = EH12 6BG\n | local_authority  Edinburgh City = \n | dfeno                   = \n | urn                     = \n | ofsted                  = \n | staff                   = \n | enrolment               = 800\n | gender                  = [[Girls]]\n | lower_age               = 3\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = 6 school houses: Argyll, Buccleuch, Douglas, Lindsay, Moray and Strathmore\n | colours                 = Red, navy, white\n | publication             = The Chronicle\n | free_label_1            = \n | free_1                  = \n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = {{URL|stge.org.uk}}\n}}\n'''St George's School for Girls''' is an all-girls' independent school situated in the [[Ravelston]] district of [[Edinburgh]], Scotland, which was rated 'Excellent' by Education Scotland in its most recent inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/inspections/|title=St George's: Scotland \u2013 A Top Girls' Private Independent Day & Boarding School|last=|first=|date=|website=www.stge.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the school celebrated the 130th anniversary of its founding in 1888.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/st-georges-130th-birthday-2018-2019/|title=St George\u2019s 130th Birthday (2018\u20132019) \u00bb St George's School For Girls|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\nSt George's is an all-through<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/staff/heads-message/show/308/all-through-schools-are-an-education-in-getting-it-right-for-kids-----alex-hems/|title=All-through Schools are an Education in Getting it Right for Kids \u2013 Alex Hems|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> girls' school from 3\u201318 years on one self-contained campus in the heart of Edinburgh. The size of the whole school is typically around 800 girls and this is divided into 3 schools based on age and stage, including an Upper School (and Sixth Form), Lower School and Junior School with a Nursery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/school-structure/|title=Our School Structure \u2013 St George's School for Girls in Edinburgh|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of the school is an important part of the story of the [[Edinburgh Association for the University Education of Women]] and there drive to create university education for women in Scotland. The first meeting had taken place in 1866 before involving [[Mary Crudelius]], [[Madeline Daniell]] and [[Sarah Mair]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/56167|title=Daniell [n\u00e9e Carter], Madeline Margaret (1832\u20131906), educationist|last=Begg|first=Tom|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=|location=Oxford|pages=|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/56167|quote=|via=}}</ref> Their aim was to get women into [[Edinburgh University]] and Walker became the \"chief intellect and administrator\".<ref name=mary/> In 1876, the ELEA decided to improve the pre-university stage of women's education and advertised classes in St. George's Hall to help women pass university entrance level qualification. They also developed correspondence courses for women who could not attend classes,<ref name=sarah>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48668;jsessionid=B3C7CC1A516DE75AA298561CB1972E2D|title=Mair, Dame Sarah Elizabeth Siddons (1846\u20131941), promoter of women's education and campaigner for women's rights|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48668|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1885 [[Mary Russell Walker]] was recalled from the [[Maria Grey Training College]] to Edinburgh<ref name=mary/> to lead the St George's Training College which would train the first women secondary school teachers in Scotland. Mary was made the head of the college and when St. George's High School for Girls was formed in 1888 she became its head as well.<ref name=mary>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48670;jsessionid=005BFE2C84D9A472593A6C9515EFAE50|title=Walker, Mary Russell (1846\u20131938), headmistress and promoter of women's education|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48670|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The first fifty students started in October 1988 using a building in Melville Street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/history/|title=Our School's History - St George's Independent Day & Boarding School|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school was the first Scottish day school for girls which taught students all the way up to university entrance level. Girls from St. George's were among the first female graduates of [[Edinburgh University]].<ref name=mary/>\n\nIn 1912 the school took its first board students<ref name=board/> and the following year St George's Training College became part of the school. By 1920 it had fifty trainee teachers.<ref name=eduni>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/education/about-us/maps-estates-history/history/part-five|title=Part 5: The Four Provincial Committees: 1907 onwards|website=The University of Edinburgh|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1939 the training college facility closed.<ref name=eduni/> During the second world war the army had the use of the school building whilst the students went south. Hallrule Hall in [[Bonchester Bridge]] became the school's temporary home from 1939 to 1942. When the students returned the building had to be renovated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/history/|title=Our School's History \u2013 St George's Independent Day & Boarding School|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nThe school's academic curriculum is a mix of GCSEs at 16 followed by Highers and Advanced Highers in the Sixth Form (S5 and S6).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/|title=St George's: Scotland \u2013 A Top Girls' Private Independent Day & Boarding School|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Examination Courses ===\nSt George\u2019s students follow two-year GCSE courses, leading to examination at age 16, at the end of S4. Most girls will take 9 subjects, including English Literature and English Language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/staff/heads-message/show/299/open-morning-speech-2019/|title=Open Morning Speech 2019|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Co-curriculum ==\nActivities include: the Model United Nations and Debating clubs.\u00a0The extensive international student exchange programme with partner schools around the globe. The Duke of Edinburgh Award and Combined Cadet Force, and charitable fundraising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/co-curriculum/|title=St George's co-curriculum programme|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A recent addition to the clubs is the engineering club in which the school are restoring a Triumph Spitfire car. The school has its own St George\u2019s [[Spitfire]] girl, Annie, who was at St George's as a boarder from 1924, with her younger sister.\u00a0 She died on 2 October 2011. Her obituary in 'The Telegraph' described how Britain's most famous fighter 'plane, the Spitfire, was named after her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/air-force-obituaries/8849075/Annie-Penrose.html|title=Annie Penrose|date=2011-10-25|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\u00a0 Her father was Sir [[Robert McLean]]{{disambiguation needed|date=April 2020}}, chairman of [[Vickers]] in the 1930s.\u00a0 He worked with the engineer [[R J Mitchell]] who was responsible for the aircraft's design.\u00a0 When the time came to name it, McLean suggested 'Spitfire', his affectionate name for his daughter, Annie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/blogs-and-news/show/134/st-george---s-spitfire-girl/|title=St George\u2019s Spitfire Girl|website=www.stge.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== International Programme ==\nThe school has a well established exchange programme with partner schools in Australia, Canada, Chile, Germany, South Africa, Spain and the United States. The school also runs digital exchanges with partner schools across the world where students collaborate on curriculum projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/upper/international-exchange-programme/|title=International Exchange Programme \u2013 St George's Girls School Edinburgh|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n=== British Council\u2019s International School Award (2017\u20132020) ===\nIn 2019 the school was awarded a two year grant to run an Erasmus + programme entitled Community and Culture. This allows girls currently in S2 (Upper 4) to work collaboratively with students in Austria and Italy. Students will visit each other\u2019s schools and learn more about what community and culture mean for them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/staff/heads-message/show/299/open-morning-speech-2019/|title=Open Morning Speech 2019|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Links with boys schools ==\nMany events are held in conjunction with the boys school Merchiston Castle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/st-georges-partners/|title=St George's School links with Merchiston Castle School for boys|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Former pupils==\n{{see also|Category:People educated at St George's School, Edinburgh}}\n* [[Kaye Adams]], Broadcaster and journalist\n* [[Katie Targett-Adams]], Musician and Recording Artist\n* [[Phyllis Bone]], Sculptor and first female member of the [[Royal Scottish Academy]]\n* [[Sheila Burnford]], novelist\n* Dr [[Cordelia Fine]], Academic Psychologist and writer<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stge.org.uk/alumnae/famous-old-girls |title=Notable Alumnae \" St George's School For Girls |publisher=Stge.org.uk |accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cordeliafine.com/about.html |title=Cordelia Fine |publisher=Cordelia Fine |accessdate=17 December 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120115559/http://www.cordeliafine.com/about.html |archivedate=20 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Candia McWilliam]], Award-winning Author\n* [[Penny Macmillan]], Journalist and broadcaster<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n* [[Kathleen Scott]], Baroness Kenett, Sculptor.\n* [[Marie Stopes]], scientist, author and pioneer in the field of birth control.\n* [[Alice Thompson]], novelist, Winner of the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] 1996\n*[[Carol Brown Janeway]], translator and editor.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1969/06/06/78348288.pdf|title=Carol Brown engaged to William H. Janeway|date=6 June 1969|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Boarding==\nThe girls from the ages of ten to eighteen live in Houldsworth House on the campus on the edge of the school grounds. The student Head of Boarding is elected by the boarders. The school has around 50 boarders, about 7% of the number of pupils.<ref>{{Citation |title=Scotland's Boarding Schools |page=117 |magazine=Scottish Field |location=Edinburgh |date=February 2013 |url=http://www.scottishfield.co.uk |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref>\nThe boarders form an integral part of the school and are made up of approximately 50% UK and 50% international students.<ref name=board>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/boarding/|title=St George's School For Girls|last=|first=|date=|website=www.stge.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> St George's School celebrated the centenary of boarding at the school in 2012.<ref>{{Citation |title=Boarding Centenary |pages=6\u201313 |magazine=The OGA (Old Girls' Association annual magazine) |location=Edinburgh |date=December 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Margaret Houldsworth]]\n*[[Sarah Mair]]\n*[[J. O. Lindsay|Jean Lindsay]], headmistress, 1960\u20131976\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Schools in Edinburgh}}\n\n{{Coord|55|57|00|N|3|14|00|W|region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Georges School Edinburgh}}\n[[Category:Independent schools in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1888]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Category B listed buildings in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Girls' Schools Association]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = St George's School for Girls\n | image                   = St_George's_School_for_Girls,_Edinburgh_Logo.png\n | image_size              = 100px\n | caption                 = St George's School for Girls, Edinburgh Logo\n | motto                   = ''Trouthe and honour, fredom and curteisye''\n | established             = 1888\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Independent school (UK)|Independent]] day and [[boarding school|boarding]]\n | religious_affiliation   = Non-denom\n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headteacher\n | head                    = Alex Hems MA Oxon\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = \n | chair                   = \n | founder                 = Dame Sarah Mair\n | specialist              = \n | address                 = Garscube Terrace\n | city                    = [[Edinburgh]]\n | county                  = City of Edinburgh\n | country                 = Scotland\n | postcode                = EH12 6BG\n | local_authority  Edinburgh City = \n | dfeno                   = \n | urn                     = \n | ofsted                  = \n | staff                   = \n | enrolment               = 800\n | gender                  = [[Girls]]\n | lower_age               = 3\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = 6 school houses: Argyll, Buccleuch, Douglas, Lindsay, Moray and Strathmore\n | colours                 = Red, navy, white\n | publication             = The Chronicle\n | free_label_1            = \n | free_1                  = \n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = {{URL|stge.org.uk}}\n}}\n'''St George's School for Girls''' is an all-girls' independent school situated in the [[Ravelston]] district of [[Edinburgh]], Scotland, which was rated 'Excellent' by Education Scotland in its most recent inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/inspections/|title=St George's: Scotland - A Top Girls' Private Independent Day & Boarding School|last=|first=|date=|website=www.stge.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the school celebrated the 130th anniversary of its founding in 1888.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/st-georges-130th-birthday-2018-2019/|title=St George\u2019s 130th Birthday (2018 \u2013 2019) \u00bb St George's School For Girls|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\nSt George's is an all-through<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/staff/heads-message/show/308/all-through-schools-are-an-education-in-getting-it-right-for-kids-----alex-hems/|title=All-through Schools are an Education in Getting it Right for Kids \u2013 Alex Hems|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> girls' school from 3\u201318 years on one self-contained campus in the heart of Edinburgh. The size of the whole school is typically around 800 girls and this is divided into 3 schools based on age and stage, including an Upper School (and Sixth Form), Lower School and Junior School with a Nursery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/school-structure/|title=Our School Structure - St George's School for Girls in Edinburgh|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of the school is an important part of the story of the [[Edinburgh Association for the University Education of Women]] and there drive to create university education for women in Scotland. The first meeting had taken place in 1866 before involving [[Mary Crudelius]], [[Madeline Daniell]] and [[Sarah Mair]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/56167|title=Daniell [n\u00e9e Carter], Madeline Margaret (1832\u20131906), educationist|last=Begg|first=Tom|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=|location=Oxford|pages=|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/56167|quote=|via=}}</ref> Their aim was to get women into [[Edinburgh University]] and Walker became the \"chief intellect and administrator\".<ref name=mary/> In 1876, the ELEA decided to improve the pre-university stage of women's education and advertised classes in St. George's Hall to help women pass university entrance level qualification. They also developed correspondence courses for women who could not attend classes,<ref name=sarah>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48668;jsessionid=B3C7CC1A516DE75AA298561CB1972E2D|title=Mair, Dame Sarah Elizabeth Siddons (1846\u20131941), promoter of women's education and campaigner for women's rights|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48668|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1885 [[Mary Russell Walker]] was recalled from the [[Maria Grey Training College]] to Edinburgh<ref name=mary/> to lead the St George's Training College which would train the first women secondary school teachers in Scotland. Mary was made the head of the college and when St. George's High School for Girls was formed in 1888 she became its head as well.<ref name=mary>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48670;jsessionid=005BFE2C84D9A472593A6C9515EFAE50|title=Walker, Mary Russell (1846\u20131938), headmistress and promoter of women's education|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48670|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The first fifty students started in October 1988 using a building in Melville Street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/history/|title=Our School's History - St George's Independent Day & Boarding School|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school was the first Scottish day school for girls which taught students all the way up to university entrance level. Girls from St. George's were among the first female graduates of [[Edinburgh University]].<ref name=mary/>\n\nIn 1912 the school took its first board students<ref name=board/> and the following year St George's Training College became part of the school. By 1920 it had fifty trainee teachers.<ref name=eduni>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/education/about-us/maps-estates-history/history/part-five|title=Part 5: The Four Provincial Committees: 1907 onwards|website=The University of Edinburgh|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1939 the training college facility closed.<ref name=eduni/> During the second world war the army had the use of the school building whilst the students went south. Hallrule Hall in [[Bonchester Bridge]] became the school's temporary home from 1939 to 1942. When the students returned the building had to be renovated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/history/|title=Our School's History - St George's Independent Day & Boarding School|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nThe school's academic curriculum is a mix of GCSEs at 16 followed by Highers and Advanced Highers in the Sixth Form (S5 and S6).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/|title=St George's: Scotland - A Top Girls' Private Independent Day & Boarding School|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Examination Courses ===\nSt George\u2019s students follow two-year GCSE courses, leading to examination at age 16, at the end of S4. Most girls will take 9 subjects, including English Literature and English Language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/staff/heads-message/show/299/open-morning-speech-2019/|title=Open Morning Speech 2019|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Co-curriculum ==\nActivities include: the Model United Nations and Debating clubs.\u00a0The extensive international student exchange programme with partner schools around the globe. The Duke of Edinburgh Award and Combined Cadet Force, and charitable fundraising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/co-curriculum/|title=St George's co-curriculum programme|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A recent addition to the clubs is the engineering club in which the school are restoring a Triumph Spitfire car. The school has its own St George\u2019s [[Spitfire]] girl, Annie, who was at St George's as a boarder from 1924, with her younger sister.\u00a0 She died on 2 October 2011. Her obituary in 'The Telegraph' described how Britain's most famous fighter 'plane, the Spitfire, was named after her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/air-force-obituaries/8849075/Annie-Penrose.html|title=Annie Penrose|date=2011-10-25|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\u00a0 Her father was Sir [[Robert McLean]]{{disambiguation needed|date=April 2020}}, chairman of [[Vickers]] in the 1930s.\u00a0 He worked with the engineer [[R J Mitchell]] who was responsible for the aircraft's design.\u00a0 When the time came to name it, McLean suggested 'Spitfire', his affectionate name for his daughter, Annie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/blogs-and-news/show/134/st-george---s-spitfire-girl/|title=St George\u2019s Spitfire Girl|website=www.stge.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== International Programme ==\nThe school has a well established exchange programme with partner schools in Australia, Canada, Chile, Germany, South Africa, Spain and the United States. The school also runs digital exchanges with partner schools across the world where students collaborate on curriculum projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/upper/international-exchange-programme/|title=International Exchange Programme - St George's Girls School Edinburgh|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n=== British Council\u2019s International School Award (2017-2020) ===\nIn 2019 the school was awarded a two year grant to run an Erasmus + programme entitled Community and Culture. This allows girls currently in S2 (Upper 4) to work collaboratively with students in Austria and Italy. Students will visit each other\u2019s schools and learn more about what community and culture mean for them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/staff/heads-message/show/299/open-morning-speech-2019/|title=Open Morning Speech 2019|website=www.stge.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Links with boys schools ==\nMany events are held in conjunction with the boys school Merchiston Castle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/about/st-georges-partners/|title=St George's School links with Merchiston Castle School for boys|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Former pupils==\n{{see also|Category:People educated at St George's School, Edinburgh}}\n* [[Kaye Adams]], Broadcaster and journalist\n* [[Katie Targett-Adams]], Musician and Recording Artist\n* [[Phyllis Bone]], Sculptor and first female member of the [[Royal Scottish Academy]]\n* [[Sheila Burnford]], novelist\n* Dr [[Cordelia Fine]], Academic Psychologist and writer<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stge.org.uk/alumnae/famous-old-girls |title=Notable Alumnae \" St George's School For Girls |publisher=Stge.org.uk |accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cordeliafine.com/about.html |title=Cordelia Fine |publisher=Cordelia Fine |accessdate=17 December 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120115559/http://www.cordeliafine.com/about.html |archivedate=20 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Candia McWilliam]], Award-winning Author\n* [[Penny Macmillan]], Journalist and broadcaster<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n* [[Kathleen Scott]], Baroness Kenett, Sculptor.\n* [[Marie Stopes]], scientist, author and pioneer in the field of birth control.\n* [[Alice Thompson]], novelist, Winner of the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] 1996\n*[[Carol Brown Janeway]], translator and editor.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1969/06/06/78348288.pdf|title=Carol Brown engaged to William H. Janeway|date=6 June 1969|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Boarding==\nThe girls from the ages of ten to eighteen live in Houldsworth House on the campus on the edge of the school grounds. The student Head of Boarding is elected by the boarders. The school has around 50 boarders, about 7% of the number of pupils.<ref>{{Citation |title=Scotland's Boarding Schools |page=117 |magazine=Scottish Field |location=Edinburgh |date=February 2013 |url=http://www.scottishfield.co.uk |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref>\nThe boarders form an integral part of the school and are made up of approximately 50% UK and 50% international students.<ref name=board>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stge.org.uk/boarding/|title=St George's School For Girls|last=|first=|date=|website=www.stge.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> St George's School celebrated the centenary of boarding at the school in 2012.<ref>{{Citation |title=Boarding Centenary |pages=6\u201313 |magazine=The OGA (Old Girls' Association annual magazine) |location=Edinburgh |date=December 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Margaret Houldsworth]]\n*[[Sarah Mair]]\n*[[J. O. Lindsay|Jean Lindsay]], headmistress, 1960\u20131976\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Schools in Edinburgh}}\n\n{{Coord|55|57|00|N|3|14|00|W|region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Georges School Edinburgh}}\n[[Category:Independent schools in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1888]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Category B listed buildings in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Girls' Schools Association]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_George%27s_School,_Edinburgh"}
{"title_page": "Sholem Shtern", "text_new": "'''Sholem Shtern''' ({{circa|1907}} \u2013 August 1990; {{lang-yi|\u05e9\u05dc\u05d5\u05dd \u05e9\u05d8\u05e2\u05e8\u05df}}) was a [[Canadian]] [[Yiddish]] poet, novelist, and [[Literary criticism|critic]], best known for his [[Verse novel|novels in verse]] depicting the life of [[History of the Jews in Canada|Jewish immigrants in Canada]].\n\nShtern was born in 1906 or 1907 in [[Tyszowce|Tishevitz]], [[Poland]], and immigrated to Canada in 1927. He was a member of a prominent Yiddish literary family in Montreal, and became associated with the [[Political radicalism|radical]] movement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shtern, Sholem [after 1927]-1990|date=19 July 2001|url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/literaryarchives/027011-200.123-e.html|website=Library and Archives Canada}}</ref> His collections of poetry include ''Nuntkejt'' (Toronto, 1929) and ''In der Fri'' (Montreal, 1945), and his novels include such works as ''In Canada'' (Montreal, 1960\u201363), a two-volume novel in Yiddish verse.<ref name=jvl>{{cite web|title=Shtern|website=Jewish Virtual Library|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/shtern|access-date=8 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shtern, Sholem}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish poets]]\n[[Category:Jewish novelists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:People from Tomasz\u00f3w Lubelski County]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-language writers]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-language poets]]\n[[Category:Yiddish culture in Canada]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n\n\n{{Canada-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Sholem Shtern''' ({{circa|1907}} \u2013 August 1990; {{lang-yi|\u05e9\u05dc\u05d5\u05dd \u05e9\u05d8\u05e2\u05e8\u05df}}) was a [[Canadian]] [[Yiddish]] poet, novelist, and [[Literary criticism|critic]], best known for his [[Verse novel|novels in verse]] depicting the life of [[History of the Jews in Canada|Jewish immigrants in Canada]]. \n\nShtern was born in 1906 or 1907 in [[Tyszowce|Tishevitz]], [[Poland]], and immigrated to Canada in 1927. He was a member of a prominent Yiddish literary family in Montreal, and became associated with the [[Political radicalism|radical]] movement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shtern, Sholem [after 1927]-1990|date=19 July 2001|url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/literaryarchives/027011-200.123-e.html|website=Library and Archives Canada}}</ref> His collections of poetry include ''Nuntkejt'' (Toronto, 1929) and ''In der Fri'' (Montreal, 1945), and his novels include such works as ''In Canada'' (Montreal, 1960\u201363), a two-volume novel in Yiddish verse.<ref name=jvl>{{cite web|title=Shtern|website=Jewish Virtual Library|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/shtern|access-date=8 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Canada-poet-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shtern, Sholem}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish poets]]\n[[Category:Jewish novelists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:People from Tomasz\u00f3w Lubelski County]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-language writers]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-language poets]]\n[[Category:Yiddish culture in Canada]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sholem_Shtern"}
{"title_page": "Mahatma Gandhi Government Arts College", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox University |\nname           = Mahatma Gandhi Government Arts College|\nimage_name     = |\ntype           = Public|\nestablished    = 1970 |\nprincipal      =  |\ncity           = [[Chalakkara]], [[Mah\u00e9, Puducherry|Mah\u00e9]] |\nstate          = [[Puducherry]] |\ncountry        = [[India]] |\ncampus        = Urban|\ncolors         = |\naffiliations   = [[Pondicherry University]] |\nwebsite        = https://mggacmahe.ac.in\n|}}\n'''Mahatma Gandhi Government Arts College''', is a general degree college located in [[Chalakkara]], [[Mah\u00e9, Puducherry|Mah\u00e9]], [[Puducherry]]. It was established in the year 1970. The college is affiliated with [[Pondicherry University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Affiliated College of Pondicherry University |url=http://www.pondiuni.edu.in/affiliate-colleges?field_collegetype_value_many_to_one=Arts+%26amp%3B+Science+Colleges&field_coursesoffered_value=&field_region_value_many_to_one=Mahe|}}</ref> This college offers different courses in arts, commerce and science.\n\n==Departments==\n\n\nDepartment of '''Physics'''\n\nDepartment of '''Chemistry'''\n\nDepartment of '''Mathematics'''\n\nDepartment of '''Zoology'''\n\nPG Department of '''Botany'''\n\nDepartment of '''Computer Science'''\n\nDepartment of '''Commerce'''\n\nDepartment of '''Economics'''\n\nDepartment of '''English'''\n\nPG Department of '''Hindi'''\n\nDepartment of '''Malayalam'''\n\nHjjjhy\n\n*Physics\n*Chemistry\n*Mathematics\n*Botany\n*Zoology\n*Computer Science\n*Commerce\n*Malayalam\n*English\n*Hindi\n*Economics\n\n==Accreditation==\nThe college is  recognized by the [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] (UGC).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=https://mggacmahe.ac.in|website=www.mggacmahe.ac.in|title=MAHATMA GANDHI GOVT. ARTS COLLEGE(MGGAC)|accessdate=2017-09-25}}\n{{coord missing|Puducherry}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Puducherry]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Colleges affiliated to Pondicherry University]]\n\n\n{{Puducherry-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox University |\nname           = Mahatma Gandhi Government Arts College|\nimage_name     = |\ntype           = Public|\nestablished    = 1970 |\nprincipal      =  |\ncity           = [[Chalakkara]], [[Mah\u00e9, Puducherry|Mah\u00e9]] |\nstate          = [[Puducherry]] |\ncountry        = [[India]] |\ncampus        = Urban|\ncolors         = |\naffiliations   = [[Pondicherry University]] |\nwebsite        = https://mggacmahe.ac.in\n|}}\n'''Mahatma Gandhi Government Arts College''', is a general degree college located in [[Chalakkara]], [[Mah\u00e9, Puducherry|Mah\u00e9]], [[Puducherry]]. It was established in the year 1970. The college is affiliated with [[Pondicherry University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Affiliated College of Pondicherry University |url=http://www.pondiuni.edu.in/affiliate-colleges?field_collegetype_value_many_to_one=Arts+%26amp%3B+Science+Colleges&field_coursesoffered_value=&field_region_value_many_to_one=Mahe|}}</ref> This college offers different courses in arts, commerce and science.\n\n==Departments==\nP\n\nDepartment of '''Physics'''\n\nDepartment of '''Chemistry'''\n\nDepartment of '''Mathematics'''\n\nDepartment of '''Zoology'''\n\nPG Department of '''Botany'''\n\nDepartment of '''Computer Science'''\n\nDepartment of '''Commerce'''\n\nDepartment of '''Economics'''\n\nDepartment of '''English'''\n\nPG Department of '''Hindi'''\n\nDepartment of '''Malayalam'''\n\n\n\n\n\n\nHjjjhy\n\n*Physics\n*Chemistry\n*Mathematics\n*Botany\n*Zoology\n*Computer Science\n*Commerce\n*Malayalam\n*English\n*Hindi\n*Economics\n\n==Accreditation==\nThe college is  recognized by the [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commissio